WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.480 --> 00:00:05.440
The Seine River is not the longest river of&nbsp;
France but it is certainly the most iconic,

00:00:05.440 --> 00:00:09.920
with its banks passing some of the&nbsp;
world’s most recognizable architecture.

00:00:09.920 --> 00:00:13.440
The river has its humble beginning&nbsp;
in the heart of the Burgundy region,

00:00:13.440 --> 00:00:19.200
where an artificial grotto and decorative statues&nbsp;
attend the start of its 777 kilometer long

00:00:19.200 --> 00:00:24.960
journey through the tranquil French countryside.
Flowing northwards, progressively larger streams

00:00:24.960 --> 00:00:30.400
contribute to the Seine as it makes its way down&nbsp;
from the Langres plateau. During this first half,

00:00:30.400 --> 00:00:36.240
the river rapidly loses elevation and by the time the&nbsp;
waters reach Paris, the banks are only 24 meters

00:00:36.240 --> 00:00:42.080
above sea level, with more than 440 kilometers&nbsp;
still to go before reaching the English Channel.

00:00:42.080 --> 00:00:46.875
As a consequence of this shallow gradient,&nbsp;
the river's current is exceptionally slow.

00:00:46.875 --> 00:00:51.600
In combination with a change in geology where&nbsp;
soft chalky plains are replacing the hard

00:00:51.600 --> 00:00:55.600
limestone escarpment, the river starts&nbsp;
heavily meandering through the Normandy.

00:00:56.320 --> 00:01:01.360
The reduced current also heavily impacts the&nbsp;
river's geometry, with a low erosive force

00:01:01.360 --> 00:01:06.560
resulting in a quite shallow river basin. This has&nbsp;
long posed a challenge for larger vessels to reach

00:01:06.560 --> 00:01:11.520
Paris, and today, most ocean-going vessels&nbsp;
are limited to the port of Rouen. However,

00:01:11.520 --> 00:01:15.680
the port's viability depends entirely&nbsp;
on continuous dredging operations to

00:01:15.680 --> 00:01:19.840
maintain a navigable channel to the Pont de&nbsp;
Normandie, one of the longest cable-stayed

00:01:19.840 --> 00:01:24.880
bridges of Europe, which marks the gateway&nbsp;
to the English Channel and the Atlantic Ocean.

00:01:24.880 --> 00:01:29.680
This shallow gradient and slow flow which&nbsp;
shapes many aspects of the Middle and Lower

00:01:29.680 --> 00:01:34.000
Seine also has the unfortunate side&nbsp;
effect of retaining pollutants far

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:38.640
longer than in faster-flowing rivers.
In historic Paris, before the advent

00:01:38.640 --> 00:01:42.560
of the industrial revolution, this&nbsp;
issue was still manageable and the

00:01:42.560 --> 00:01:47.200
Seine is often depicted as a place for&nbsp;
fishing and bathing in Impressionist art.

00:01:47.200 --> 00:01:50.960
With the rise of factories around the river&nbsp;
banks, however, the Seine’s self-cleaning

00:01:50.960 --> 00:01:56.480
capabilities were quickly strained. A foul smell&nbsp;
and sluggish black river water eventually gave

00:01:56.480 --> 00:02:01.120
the Seine the nickname of “the open sewer”&nbsp;
from the beginning of the 20th century.

00:02:01.120 --> 00:02:06.080
Instead of stopping the pollution, Parisians&nbsp;
rather opted to ban swimming in 1923 and kept

00:02:06.080 --> 00:02:11.360
dumping more and more waste into the river, with&nbsp;
nitrate fertilizer runoff making the 1960s the

00:02:11.360 --> 00:02:16.240
most toxic decade yet. During this time, the&nbsp;
river has almost been declared dead and devoid

00:02:16.240 --> 00:02:21.600
of marine life with a mere three species left&nbsp;
that were able to survive in the polluted water.

00:02:21.600 --> 00:02:26.000
While attempts have been made to revitalize&nbsp;
the river from the end of the 20th century,

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:30.400
it wasn’t until the preparations for the&nbsp;
Olympic games in 2024 that any significant

00:02:30.400 --> 00:02:36.720
successes could be documented. Finally,&nbsp;
in July 2025, 102 years after the initial ban,

00:02:36.720 --> 00:02:40.560
significant progress in pollution control&nbsp;
allowed the swimming ban to be lifted,

00:02:40.560 --> 00:02:45.120
though monitoring and temporary bans&nbsp;
will continue for the foreseeable future.

00:02:45.120 --> 00:02:49.200
If you want to learn about the&nbsp;actual
largest river within French territory,

00:02:49.200 --> 00:02:52.800
you can check out this video about the&nbsp;
Rhine river on the border with Germany,&nbsp;

00:02:52.800 --> 00:02:57.920
or watch what youtube thinks is best for&nbsp;
you here. See you in the next one, cheers.

